<HEADLINE>
FT  23 MAY 92 / Finance &amp; The Family: The Week Ahead
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A FIRST profit contribution from the US should help Body Shop International,
the eco-friendly retailer of beauty products, to a 25 per cent-plus increase
in pre-tax profits. A figure of Pounds 25m to Pounds 26m is expected when
the full-year results are announced on Wednesday. With UK growth limited by
recession, the turnround in the relatively new US chain will be a critical
factor alongside continued progress on the continent.
Carlton Communications, the television and television services group, is
expected to announce a modest increase in interim pre-tax profits on
Wednesday. Analysts are predicting around Pounds 48m, which suggests that
Carlton has still been suffering from recession. The Pounds 46.3m figure
last year was nearly 30 per cent down on 1990.
When MEPC, the UK's second largest property company, reports its interim
results on Thursday, attention will be focused on its development programme,
which is the largest in the sector.
Analysts will be particularly keen to hear of any progress in letting Alban
Gate, the largely-empty office block straddling London Wall in the City. The
pre-tax profits for the half year to March 1992 are expected to be around
Pounds 63m, down from Pounds 67.4m a year ago. Although the rental income is
likely to rise, this will be offset by an increase in financing costs as the
company reduces the proportion of capitalised interest associated with
development properties.
On the same day, Thorn EMI is expected to report annual pre-tax profits
slightly down from last time's Pounds 258.6m to about Pounds 255m, although
they could fall as low as Pounds 240m. Recent acquisitions - the half of
Chrysalis Records which Thorn did not already own, Remco America, and Virgin
Music Group, this latter only acquired at the beginning of March - will
probably have boosted the pre-tax line, though earnings are likely to be
down around 10 per cent.
