FT  23 MAY 92 / Legal clash may harm Channel 5 prospects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROSPECTS of a merger between Five TV and The Entertainment Channel, both
bidders for the Channel 5 franchise, appeared to be damaged yesterday after
Five TV signalled it might continue its legal battle against TV-am.
Five TV yesterday lost its High Court action to gain an injunction
preventing TV-am from investing in The Entertainment Channel, but later
indicated that it could take the issue to a full hearing.
No hearing could be held before the July 7 deadline for franchise bids, but
the clash could reduce the chances of the consortia joining forces. Several
leading shareholders in both consortia believe high start-up costs mean that
the Channel 5 franchise will be viable only if the bid is uncontested and
the minimum Pounds 1,000-a-year bid made.
The vice-chancellor, Sir Donald Nicholls, said an exclusivity and
confidentiality clause signed by TV-am when it was shown Five TV's business
plan should not prevent it from investing in any rival Channel 5 bidder.
