<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAY 92 / International Company News: Japan's trading companies post
fall in earnings, sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S big six trading companies yesterday reported an expected fall in
both sales and earnings for the fiscal year that ended March 31 due to the
global economic slowdown and sour financial investments.
Weaker domestic demand curbed import revenues, while there was also a
decline in income from third-country transactions. In terms of product
sectors, there was a decline in turnover from energy and chemical products
as crude oil prices fell. A price drop for metals also depressed income. But
sales of machinery rose for some companies.
Most of the trading houses expect pre-tax earnings will remain flat or rise
only slightly during the current fiscal year reflecting the gradual recovery
of the global economy.
C. Itoh &amp; Co retained its position as the world's biggest trading company
with Y20,000bn (Dollars 154.26bn) in sales, but it suffered its first profit
fall in five years with pre-tax earnings declining by 16.7 per cent to
Y45.28bn. After-tax profits plunged by 42.7 per cent to Y10.9bn as
extraordinary losses amounted to Y5.9bn. C. Itoh predicts sales will fall
slightly to Y19,000bn in the current fiscal year, while pre-tax profit will
be steady at Y45bn. The after-tax profit is expected to rise to Y12bn.
Sumitomo Corp reported an 18.1 per cent fall in pre-tax earnings to Y63.25bn
as its net financial income was cut by 48 per cent to Y13bn. This reflected
a decline in net interest and dividend income and losses on securities.
Sumitomo predicts pre-tax earnings will increase slightly to Y66bn as sales
reach Y19,000bn. After-tax profits are expected to reach Y34bn.
Marubeni had the sharpest pre-tax earnings setback among the top trading
companies with a 29.9 per cent drop to Y38.4bn. Its deficit on net financial
items nearly doubled to Y20.6bn due to a fall in interest and dividend
income. But its after-tax profit increased by 2.2 per cent to Y17.4bn as
extraordinary losses eased. It expects pre-tax and after-tax earnings to
remain steady this fiscal year, while sales should decline slightly to
Y17,000bn.
Mitsui and Co performed better than than its competitors with a 7.1 per cent
fall in pre-tax earnings to Y61.4bn. It narrowed its deficit in financial
income to Y5.9bn from Y19.8bn in the previous fiscal year.
Its after-tax profit grew by 1.7 per cent to Y22.6bn as it reduced its
extraordinary losses, mostly connected with the ill-fated Iranian joint
venture petrochemical project, to Y10.2bn from Y29bn a year ago.
It expects moderate rises in its pre-tax and after-tax earnings to Y62bn and
Y23bn respectively in the current fiscal year, while sales should increase
by 2 per cent to Y16,500bn.
Mitsubishi Corp had the highest pre-tax profit at Y85.89bn among the main
trading companies, although it represented a decline of 8.9 per cent. It was
the only trading house to predict a significant earnings drop this fiscal
year, despite a slight rise in sales to Y16bn. It estimated pre-tax earnings
will fall by 20 per cent to Y70bn and after-tax profits by 25 per cent to
Y30bn. But analysts cautioned that Mitsubishi is normally conservative in
its forecasts.
Nissho Iwai had the sharpest fall in sales with an 18.2 per cent decline to
Y10,900bn. It predicts a 5.4 per cent decrease in pre-tax profits to Y20bn.
</TEXT>
