<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAY 92 / SEC suggests share change rule
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FOREIGN investment companies could find it considerably easier to sell their
shares in the US under a rule change being considered by the Securities and
Exchange Commission, the US securities industry watchdog.
In a report yesterday, the SEC's investment management division proposed
that some foreign funds should be allowed to offer their shares in the US
without having to register with the SEC. In theory, this could cover the
likes of British investment trust shares or unit trusts.
However, the staff report suggested that these foreign funds would need to
demonstrate that regulation in their home country provided a level of
investor protection which was 'substantially equivalent' to that provided by
the SEC. It also called for attempts to establish 'reciprocity', so that US
funds would have access to foreign markets.
The recommendation comes as part of a review of the 1940 Investment Company
Act, which covers investment management regulation in the US. The SEC has
been considering revisions to the rules for the past two years.
The report also recommends deregulating sales charges for mutual funds in
the US; allowing funds to redeem shares at specific intervals; and exempting
from SEC registration funds that are limited to sophisticated investors.
In the past, foreign funds have found it difficult to offer shares in the
US, without effectively becoming US investment companies. No foreign
investment company has registered in the US since 1973.
Some of recommendations - including the sale of non-US mutual funds in the
US - would require legislative changes. One US lawyer said yesterday that an
earlier proposal to allow non-US mutual funds to sell products in the US
failed to get through the legislature in 1984.
The proposed changes were broadly welcomed by the Investment Company
Institute. However, on the issue of 'increased internationalisation', it
warned that the proposed legislative changes 'might not provide sufficient
protection for US investors investing in foreign funds or effective market
access for US funds seeking to offer their shares abroad'.
</TEXT>
