<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: PM denies failure on repossessions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John Major yesterday denied that the government's scheme to help people
facing home repossessions had been a 'complete flop' as he clashed in the
Commons with Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader, during Prime Minister's
questions.
Under a scheme announced last December, the government agreed to pay the
mortgage interest element of social security benefits direct to lenders.
In return, the mortgage lenders agreed not to repossess the homes of people
covered by such benefits.
In addition the lenders would set aside up to Pounds 1bn for
mortgage-to-rent schemes under which housing associations would buy the
homes of repossessed borrowers and rent them back to their former owners.
Put on the defensive by Mr Kinnock's charge, Mr Major retorted by saying
that 'only about half a per cent' of home-owners had had their homes
repossessed, and claimed that repossessions often resulted from domestic
difficulties within families.
In a testy series of exchanges, he defended measures taken by Mr Norman
Lamont, the chancellor, maintaining that they were helping to alleviate
problems.
Many mortgage lenders had agreed not to repossess homes where mortgage
interest was covered by income support, he said.
He finally rounded on Mr Kinnock, accusing him of being hypocritical on the
issue. 'It is your party that would have denied 1.5m people from becoming
homeowners in the first place,' he said.
Mr Kinnock had opened by inquiring whether Mr Major would still claim, as he
had in January, that the government had stopped housing repossessions
'before Christmas'.
Pointing out that Mr Lamont had promised that the government's rescue plan
would reduce repossessions by 40,000, Mr Kinnock said despite this, 'action
was started' against 42,000 families in the first three months of this year.
Branding the government scheme a 'complete flop', he urged the prime
minister to 'start taking steps to ensure we have an effective scheme before
thousands more families are put out of their homes'.
For the small percentage affected, repossession was a '100 per cent
tragedy', while many more families were under 'intense pressure' on mortgage
payments.
'It is necessary in a country where there could be 80,000 repossessions
again this year for the government to introduce a proper mortgage rescue
scheme.'
The exchange was prefaced by a question from Mr Chris Smith, a shadow
Treasury spokesman, who urged the government to allow local authorities to
use more than Pounds 6bn of capital receipts in their hands to build more
homes.
</TEXT>
