<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Move to fixed terms is ruled out
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A MOVE to fixed-term parliaments and the ending of the prime minister's
right to choose the date of general elections was rejected by Mr John Major
yesterday.
He firmly rebuffed a suggestion by a Labour MP that pre-determined general
election dates would increase democracy.
There was a five-year limit to the length of parliaments, Mr Major said, but
the element of flexibility was 'part of our constitution'.
'It is right, it is helpful and it is not going to be changed,' he added at
prime minister's questions.
The Labour party backs fixed-term parliaments, and Mr Major's comments will
disappoint MPs who had hoped his commitment to reforming the Commons
procedures would extend to the calling of general election dates.
Mr Andrew MacKinlay, Labour MP for Thurrock, told Mr Major that 'the
capacity of any prime minister to manipulate the decision-making process,
and choose a time to create a window of opportunity, is wholly undemocratic
and betrays your bogus reforming credentials'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6611</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEVA2AEPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920522
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Council cash delay confirmed
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A DELAY in the usual arrangements for announcing next year's council
spending was confirmed yesterday by Mr John Redwood, local government
minister.
Ministers usually give in July the overall figures for local authority
spending.
Mr Redwood said, however, that the move to the council tax and the change in
local authorities' responsibility for community care were special factors
that made it sensible to postpone the announcement until the autumn, when
the detailed arrangements will also be published.
Normally, the overall figures are used in discussions during the summer
between local authority associations and environment department officials.
The delay will reinforce fears that the arrangements for the first year of
council tax will be made at the last minute.
Mr Redwood said the scale of a transitional relief scheme for the move to
council tax could not be properly assessed until the valuation exercise had
been completed, and that the necessary information would not be available in
July.
The postponement has been seen by Labour MPs as a sign that local government
will face a particularly tough settlement in this year's public spending
round.
</TEXT>
