<TEXT>
THE Irish government was rebuked by a Northern Ireland Office minister
yesterday for publicly urging the withdrawal of the Parachute Regiment from
Northern Ireland, Ralph Atkins writes.
Mr Michael Mates, the security minister, told MPs that 'megaphone diplomacy
in this sort of case seldom helps'. The 1985 Anglo-Irish Agreement
established a joint secretariat through which disputes could be resolved in
private, he said.
Mr David Andrews, the Irish foreign minister, called for the regiment to be
withdrawn from the province after clashes between soldiers and civilians in
Coalisland, County Tyrone, last weekend.
At Commons questions, Mr Mates confirmed that the regiment would remain in
the province and told MPs that 'it is best if these matters are kept for
private discussions, and we have a mechanism for doing so'.
