<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAY 92 / Parliament and Politics: Foot soldiers dig in for war of
attrition - Alison Smith gauges the mettle of Westminster's Euro-rebels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNDETERRED by their failure to stop the bill last night, the cross-party
bands of Euro-rebels will be fighting on - and fighting to win - as the
legislation proceeds through Westminster.
Once it became clear that Labour would try to block the bill only and
specifically on the grounds of opposing the UK's opting out of the social
chapter and economic and monetary union - a course which would not attract
any Tory rebels - the Euro-sceptics knew they would not be able to stop it
in its tracks.
At last week's Tory Euro-sceptics' dinner at the Carlton Club - even before
the numbers of rebels had hardened - the talk was of tactics during the
bill's committee stage, when MPs as a whole will be able to discuss it in
detail and propose amendments to it.
The critical question for the rebels will be whether they can devise an
amendment which could unite elements as disparate as the Labour frontbench
and hardened Euro-sceptics such as Sir Teddy Taylor on the Tory side.
In any event, there is certain to be an attempt to propose a referendum, and
though this might lead the pro-European Liberal Democrats to vote with some
Tory Euro-sceptics, it may be difficult for the Labour party to agree.
The two options open to the rebels for handling the bill are co-operation or
delay. With co-operation, perhaps four full days would be set aside for
discussion of the main issues. There are votes, which they are likely to
lose, but at least the arguments would have been given a hearing.
But if the rebels - or even a small minority of them - decide to filibuster
in a bid to delay the bill, then the government might seek to impose a
timetable on discussion, perhaps by then with popular support from
backbenchers on both sides of the Commons.
Alternatively, it could simply threaten a later summer recess.
Though either route ends in the passage of the bill, both parties have been
making strenuous efforts to minimise the rebellion.
Particular pressure has been applied to new MPs, with more success on the
Tory side than on the opposition.
Mr Llew Smith, the Labour MP for Blaenau Gwent, used his maiden speech to
explain why he was going to vote against the bill instead of following the
party line of abstaining. Mr Nick Harvey, the new Liberal Democrat MP for
Devon North, abstained rather than following his colleagues in voting for
the bill.
More generally, reminders that none of the rebels seemed to have mentioned
to the electorate just a few weeks ago that they were planning to vote
against party policy have been coming from the two frontbenches. There have
also been touching appeals to logic, party unity and detailed argument when
in many cases the view held is more instinctive and high-flown.
On both sides, the rebels include a few figures, such as Mr John Biffen and
Mr Peter Shore, whose seniority even those wholly unsympathetic to their
stance say gives the rebellion 'a bit of class'.
'I don't feel as though I'm backing a loser,' said one senior rebel, 'but
I'm not sure we'll win in my lifetime.'
</TEXT>
