<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAY 92 / 400 Names face average Pounds 80,000 loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ABOUT 400 Lloyd's Names will learn this week that they must pay an average
of more than Pounds 80,000 each to meet losses sustained since 1983 by
syndicate 387, which specialised in offering stop-loss reinsurance policies
to other Names.
Syndicate 387's losses for 1989 alone amount to Pounds 32.93m - more than
five times the size of its stamp or capital base, and one of the worst
results produced by any of the 401 syndicates trading at the Lloyd's
insurance market in 1989. Lloyd's is expected next month to report a loss of
between Pounds 1.6bn and Pounds 1.8bn for 1989, according to the latest
estimates.
The affairs of more than 70 per cent of the syndicate's Names were handled
by agencies linked to the Lime Street agency. Names will be asked to meet
the losses by mid July.
The syndicate was formerly managed by the Gooda Walker agency, which went
into liquidation last October. Many of the Names - individuals whose assets
back underwriting - already face severe underwriting losses as a result of
their membership of syndicates managed by Gooda Walker, Rose Thomson Young
and other agencies which underwrote spiral reinsurance business, in which
syndicates and London market companies reinsure each others' exposure to
catastrophe loss.
Syndicate 387's present managers, GW Run Off, have called in cash to meet
losses on five separate underwriting years, 1983, 1984, 1985, 1988 and 1989.
All have been left open because of uncertainty about future claims. Losses
for the five years amount to Pounds 54.93m.
Mr Ralph Sharp of GW Run Off said that the deterioration on the earlier
years was because of increasing losses from pollution and asbestos-related
claims, many of which emerge many years later. The losses for 1989 could
eventually amount to more than Pounds 43m, according to Mr Sharp.
In the years from 1983 to 1989 the syndicate's membership ranged from 239 to
448, but many were members in more than one year. In 1989 a handful of Names
committed between Pounds 30,000 and Pounds 40,000, and face losses of up to
Pounds 300,000 each.
An early-day motion concerning alleged malpractice by professionals at
Lloyd's was withdrawn from the Commons order paper yesterday. The motion had
been tabled by two Tory MPs - Mr Paul Marland, MP for Gloucestershire West,
and Mr Henry Bellingham, MP for Norfolk North West.
</TEXT>
