<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAY 92 / Paying price of peace dividend: David White on the battle
for survival at two naval dockyards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S two main naval dockyards are fighting a highly politicised battle
for survival. The private-sector companies which have been running the yards
since 1987 believe their fate will be sealed within the next year.
When the two refit yards - Devonport Royal Dockyard at Plymouth and Rosyth
Royal Dockyard in Fife - were placed under private-sector management in
1987, the change was hotly contested by unions.
Both yards have been through heavy redundancy programmes paid for by the
government. At Devonport, with an annual turnover of about Pounds 270m, jobs
have fallen from more than 11,000 to just over 5,000. Rosyth, with a Pounds
180m turnover, has cut the number of jobs from about 6,000 to 4,200.
The Ministry of Defence, which still owns the facilities, guaranteed the
managers a 'core programme' for refitting surface ships and submarines -
about two thirds of naval work with the rest being put out to competition or
carried out by the Royal Navy's maintenance yard at Portsmouth. The
programme has now been substantially reduced. Fleet numbers are being cut,
some vessels have been paid off early, and the latest ships need less
frequent work.
Devonport Management (DML), a consortium in which the main partners are
Brown and Root of the US, Balfour Beatty (part of BICC) and Weir Group, says
its warship refit work has been cut by 45 per cent compared with the
original programme.
Mr Mike Leece, managing director, thinks the whole naval industry -
shipbuilding and refit - will provide no more than 11,000 to 12,000 jobs in
the late 1990s compared with 30,000 in the mid 1980s.
The crucial decision under consideration at the MoD is on new refuelling and
refitting facilities for nuclear-powered submarines. Refitting of the UK's
Polaris ballistic-missile submarines is done at Rosyth and work on
nuclear-propelled 'hunter-killer' submarines is split between Rosyth and
Devonport. Both DML and Babcock Thorn, the management consortium at Rosyth,
believe the logical option is to concentrate this work in a single site.
Cranes and lorries are already busy at the Rosyth yard on a facility known
as RD57 to accommodate Trident submarines, the successors to Polaris.
Plans include two dry docks and an integrated refuelling site. About Pounds
50m has already been spent, and the overall cost was originally put at
Pounds 450m. DML says it could provide similar facilities for less than
Pounds 200m and that the extra work would greatly increase its efficiency.
Babcock Thorn is discussing a low-cost alternative to its original plan at
Rosyth which it says would reduce the further spending needed there to
Pounds 150m.
Both yards have diversified into areas such as refurbishing rail stock and
boat building, but both see their future pinned to submarine business.
The MoD is due to tell them by October 5 whether it proposes to renew their
contracts, which expire in April 1994.
Both dockyards are next to naval bases - another area under review at the
MoD. DML argues that the Navy, needing to find substantial savings in
support costs, cannot sustain three bases in the south - Plymouth,
Portsmouth and the smaller establishment at Portland - and that the whole
complex could be at risk, affecting 10,000 jobs.
Mr Leece says: 'At the end of the day one of us is going to pay the bloody
peace dividend.'
SIGNIFICANT delays and cost overruns in the refitting of naval vessels at
the Devonport and Rosyth dockyards have been highlighted by the National
Audit Office, the public spending watchdog.
In a report published yesterday the audit office underlined the problems of
high overhead costs and excess capacity at the yards and said the defence
ministry must determine how much of the facilities it would need in the long
term. The report recognises that commercial managers had improved efficiency
but said there was no way of assessing the net savings achieved since the
MoD handed over the running of the yards.
The audit office calculates that under-utilised staff and facilities at the
yards cost Pounds 53m in 1990-91.
Ministry of Defence: Operation of the Royal Dockyards under Commercial
Management. HMSO. Pounds 7.80.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-6622</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CEVA2AEEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920522
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAY 92 / Staple defends staff and his predecessor's record
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE and JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN SPITE OF criticism of the Serious Fraud Office over the collapse of the
second Guinness trial and its handling of the Blue Arrow prosecution, the
new director appears relaxed about the SFO's ability to do the job.
At a press conference yesterday following publication of the SFO annual
report Mr George Staple mounted a staunch defence of the competence of his
staff and the record of his predecessor, Mrs Barbara Mills QC, now the
director of public prosecutions.
Before the Roskill fraud trials committee report, prosecution of serious
fraud was a problem. The SFO had changed that, Mr Staple said. The SFO's
conviction rate rose last year from 63 per cent to 66 per cent. The office
prosecuted 58 people in 28 trials. Twenty defendants were jailed.
Nevertheless, he admits to the strains on his department of coping with the
burgeoning of cases of detected fraud. The increased value of the cases
being reported has led to the raising of the SFO's limit for taking on new
cases from Pounds 2m to Pounds 5m.
This is in spite of a big increase in the SFO's budget, which rose from
Pounds 13.2m in 1990-91 to Pounds 17.8m last year and Pounds 21.2m this
year. Much of this increase was a result of having to mount the BCCI and
Maxwell inquiries.
'If we had the funds no doubt we could prosecute more cases - there is a lot
of serious fraud about,' Mr Staple said. 'But that is up to the government.
I feel we are doing enough to be a real deterrent.'
Confronted with the debate on how regulators and the legal profession should
best tackle the problems of combating white-collar crime, Mr Staple believes
that because the SFO is less than four years old it is not the time for
fundamental change.
He rejects an enhanced regulatory role for the office giving it powers
similar to the Securities and Exchange Commission in the US. The existing
demarcations between the SFO, Department of Trade and Industry and the Stock
Exchange work well at the moment and should not be tampered with, he said.
There are changes to trial procedures which he would like to see to counter
some of the criticism of the length of recent cases. The defence should be
forced to disclose its hand at a much earlier stage. That would allow the
prosecution to refine its case thereby reducing the overall length of the
trial. He denied that this would amount to a further erosion of a suspect's
right to silence.
A procedure for agreeing non-contentious evidence in advance of the trial
would also save time, he said. But he rejected the suggestion that the SFO
itself could make the greatest contribution to cutting the length of cases
if it abandoned its approach of throwing the book at defendants and
concentrated on the best six or 10 counts.
'The SFO is bound by the Crown Prosecution Services' code which requires us
not to charge people on the fringes of a cases only the people at its core,'
he said. 'And, equally, we are required not to overload the indictment. But
we can't be put in a straitjacket. These cases are big and they are complex.
Justice often requires a number of defendants and a number of charges.'
Mr Staple did not reject out of hand the introduction of some form of plea
bargaining in serious fraud cases.
</TEXT>
