<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAY 92 / Jump in lending suggests growing confidence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIGNS that confidence among businesses and consumers is improving were
boosted yesterday by news that bank and building society lending roselast
month.
The Bank of England said lending by banks and building societies to the
private and corporate sectors - M4 lending - grew by Pounds 5.1bn in the
month. The sharp jump suggested an increase in building society loans for
house purchases.
Economists warned against reading too much into one month's figures, and
said much of the growth was a rebound from March, when companies and
individuals made repayments totalling Pounds 400m net. It was the first time
since 1982 that repayments on bank and building society lending outstripped
new loans.
The modestly encouraging news from the Bank was backed by figures from the
British Bankers' Association, the trade body for Britain's nine biggest
banking groups. The figures showed that lending by the association's members
to the private sector grew by Pounds 2.6bn last month, the largest rise
since the statistics began a year ago. This increase followed a net
repayment by the private sector of almost Pounds 1.75bn in March. According
to the association's figures, lending to individuals for house buying grew
by Pounds 402m compared with a rise of Pounds 197m in April last year.
The figures also showed that consumers continued to repay debt. Last month
consumers repaid a net Pounds 43m on personal loans including overdrafts,
loans for cars, and credit card loans, compared with a rise of Pounds 103m
in April last year. Within the company sector, bank lending to securities
dealers grew by Pounds 306m, to wholesalers by Pounds 200m and to
manufacturers by Pounds 196m. Those figures were offset by net repayments
from leasing, construction and property companies. 'One should never draw
conclusions from one month's figures since they may be erratic,' said Lord
Inchyra, association secretary-general. 'It is particularly difficult in a
month like this, where there is a very large seasonal adjustment, to point
to any clear signs of an upturn in the demand for credit.'
Figures for money supply growth were in line with expectations. Narrow
money, or M0, which comprises mostly notes and coins in circulation and
represents underlying demand pressures, rose 0.4 per cent last month to give
a 2.3 per cent increase for the year. M0 growth in the year to March it was
2.2 per cent. M4 rose by 0.8 per cent last month, bringing the year-on-year
growth rate to 5.7 per cent.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
