FT  22 MAY 92 / Company register reform is urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHAMBERS of Commerce are to press the government to support the
establishment of a mandatory trading register for all companies along the
lines already adopted by many EC countries.
Representatives of the chambers are to meet Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and
industry secretary, on June 8 to seek ministerial backing for a wide-ranging
overhaul of the system of registration.
The initiative is designed to simplify and speed up the process of company
licensing and registration and to improve the flow of commercial information
available.
Mr Richard Brown, director of policy for the Association of British Chambers
of Commerce, told the association's conference in Brighton that British
companies faced heavy burdens of compliance.
The report of an association working party on the issue presented to the
conference says there is widespread confusion and ignorance, particularly
among new businesses, about regulatory and licensing requirements.
Mr Brown said British companies had to compete with a culture which sought
to inhibit business and had to deal with regulatory bodies which sometimes
appeared set on preventing the creation of wealth.
There was, he claimed, considerable scope for streamlining the process of
obtaining registration or licences. The chambers were proposing - in place
of the existing piecemeal approvals - a network of trading formalities
centres where the registration process would be co-ordinated. The centres
would provide a 'one-stop' entry point at which all businesses could quickly
establish the necessary procedures for compliance.
Chambers say many business opportunities are lost because of the
'information gap'.
</TEXT>
