<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAY 92 / White House rejects charge of Iraq cover-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR members of the Bush administration yesterday angrily rejected
Congressional charges that the White House was trying to cover up
improprieties related to more than Dollars 4bn of loans to Iraq by Italy's
Banca Nazionale del Lavoro.
In testimony before the House of Representatives banking committee, Mr
Lawrence Eagleburger, deputy secretary of state, attacked the committee's
release of classified documents which, he claimed, had led to 'distortions
of the record, half-truths, and outright falsehoods, all combined into
spurious conspiracy theories and charges of a cover-up.'
He was referring to a series of Bush administration documents made public by
Mr Henry Gonzalez, committee chairman, who has argued that the documents
show a pattern of administration financial assistance to Iraq and possible
knowledge of the secret BNL loans, made from the bank's branch at Atlanta,
Georgia.
Mr Gonzalez criticised President George Bush for failure to provide Congress
with a series of BNL-related documents.
In reply, Mr Eagleburger said the administration would not permit the
further release of documents without fresh assurances that they would be
kept confidential by Congress.
Mr Eagleburger and Mr John Robson, deputy treasury secretary, testified that
there had been insufficient evidence of any Iraqi wrongdoing in the BNL
affair, in November 1989, for a senior White House meeting to block the
extension of Dollars 1bn of separate, government-guaranteed loans to
Baghdad.
Mr Eagleburger stated that these US government-guaranteed loans for Iraqi
purchase of US agricultural goods were seen by the Reagan and Bush
administrations as a tool to moderate Iraq's President Saddam Hussein. 'It
didn't work,' admitted Mr Eagleburger.
Mr Edward Kelley, a member of the Federal Reserve's board of governors, made
clear that, at the White House meeting, the Fed had firmly opposed more US
export credit loan guarantees for Iraq because of concern about the BNL case
and Iraq's credit-worthiness.
</TEXT>
