<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAY 92 / Major gives warm welcome to accord
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR gave an enthusiastic welcome to the farm talks deal yesterday.
He said an agreement on reforming the Common Agricultural Policy would be
good for farmers, consumers and the future of world trade.
Although consumers will have to wait until the middle of the decade before
benefiting from cheaper food prices, British farmers welcomed the end of the
uncertainty surrounding their businesses.
'It would appear that John Gummer (agriculture minister) has achieved quite
a remarkable victory on behalf of all UK arable farmers,' the managing
director of a large farming company said.
He was delighted that Britain had not been left at a disadvantage to smaller
European competitors.
Speaking in the House of Commons, Mr Major said that the deal was good news
for the British farmer, for the British consumer, for the General Agreement
on Tariffs and Trade negotiations, for world trade and for many developing
countries.
He congratulated Mr Gummer on his negotiating stance during the marathon
Brussels negotiating session.
The prime minister made it clear that the accord was closely in tune with
the thrust of Britain's own proposals, which were designed to protect
farmers while progressively reducing the EC's massive stocks of agricultural
products.
Whitehall officials said that the proposed shift towards a system of farm
payments tied to supporting incomes rather than paying for surpluses could
provide the background for a deal with the US in the stalled Uruguay round
of world trade talks.
More specifically, they welcomed the fact that the proposals to compensate
cereals farmers for taking land out of production took account of the much
larger average size of British farms.
Labour warned that the reforms were as likely to fail in reducing surpluses
as previous efforts had been.
Mr David Clark, shadow agriculture minister, said that the only effects
would be that 'the cost to the UK taxpayers will increase in each of the
next few years; the consumer will not benefit; farmers will get large
pay-offs.'
While Britain's farmers expressed relief that uncertainty had been resolved,
reaction in France was tougher, where farmers condemned the deal and said
that they would take to the streets immediately in protest.
German farmers said subsidy cuts would lead to collapse in many farm
regions, which would be hit by drastic price cuts in grain and other crops.
Italian farming lobbies reacted angrily to reforms which left their country
out in the cold. 'This is a completely unsatisfactory deal,' an association
of farmers said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
