<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAY 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Recovery in coarse grain
production forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WORLD coarse grain production, which is expected to fall to less than 800m
tonnes this year from 829.9m tonnes in 1990, is expected to recover in the
1992-93 season, according to the International Wheat Council.
The IWC's latest report gives a first estimate for the 1992-93 coarse grain
harvest of 825m tonnes, an increase over this season of 27m tonnes. This
season's low harvest is attributed to dry weather conditions in many growing
areas.
The largest increases are expected in the US, up 30m to 249m tonnes, and the
former Soviet Union, up just over 10m to 92.8m tonnes. However, The IWC
warns that the former Soviet Union's harvest could end up being affected by
shortages of fuel, quality seeds, fertilisers, pesticides and spare parts
for agricultural machinery.
Consumption is estimated at 820m tonnes, little changed from the previous
two years. Consumption in developing countries is expected to increase
slightly.
</TEXT>
