</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KUALA LUMPUR
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUBBER prices are poised for upturn on the back of increased demand, even
though turmoil in the world's top grower Thailand has failed to spark a
rally, an International Natural Rubber Organisation (INRO) official said,
Reuter reports from Kuala Lumpur.
'I expect a gradual improvement in prices in the second half of this year,'
said buffer stock manager Mr Aldo Hofmeister. 'Prices could rise by 10 per
cent by the end of the year from current levels due to increase in offtake.'
'But there is very little (market) reaction to developments in Thailand and
that is surprising,' he said. The INRO uses a buffer stock mechanism to
stabilise prices.
Prices in Singapore and other major markets inched up marginally on Monday
and Tuesday on fears of reduced Thai supplies. But prices eased in Singapore
yesterday.
