FT  22 MAY 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Brazil set to lift orange juice
exports by 37.5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BILL HINCHBERGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EXPORTS of Brazilian orange juice and derivatives should reach Dollars 1.4bn
for the 1991-92 harvest season, based on preliminary figures for the first
10 months of the July-June cycle, according to the Association of Brazilian
Citrus Exporters (Abicitrus).
That figure would represent a 37.5 per cent increase over the previous
season's receipts.
Through the end of April, Brazilian exports of 798,000 tonnes had generated
sales of Dollars 1.2bn. Overall export receipts for 1990-91 were Dollars
1.0bn.
Better prices and sales of stocks are responsible for the improvement, said
Mr Ademerval Garcia, Abicitrus president. Production, he said, is about the
same as last season.
The average price in 1991 was Dollars 900 per tonne/fob. This year, the
average is Dollars 1,186 per tonne/fob. Carry over last season was 336,000
tonnes, compared to 157,000 this season.
Brazilian exporters are eyeing Japan with more interest, since it eliminated
its import quotas for orange juice. Currently, 4 per cent of Brazilian
exports are shipped to Japan, compared to 48.5 per cent to the European
Community.
